main event: Over thirty unidentified objects were sighted in the sky over Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada on October 9, 1963, observed by several witnesses between 7:00 P.M. and 8:30 P.M.
interesting points: The objects were observed making rapid, irregular movements, brightening and dimming intermittently, and heading in all directions over an area about 15 degrees in extent.

The observer felt confident that the sighting was genuine and that what was observed was not a star, but rather a self-luminous object appearing to the naked eye and having a relatively unfamiliar motion within the solar system.
The objects were tracked on radar, with detailed information provided on their positions, speeds, and directions of movement.
The observer had previously seen a similar object hovering over their house for about 5 minutes on October 9, 1963 at 8:55 P.M.
The observer reported the sighting to the National Investigations Committee on Aerial Phenomena (NICAP) on the same day.
